WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.840
G'day, I'm Dean Marchiori. I'm a statistician from Sydney, Australia, and I'm interested

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:15.520
in reproducible analysis and workflow choices in R. But in my day-to-day practice in industry

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:21.420
as a commercial data scientist, is my work actually reproducible? To answer this, I conducted

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:28.320
a reproducibility retrospective, or ReproRetro. I went back through the last year of my commercial

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:32.919
data science projects, and rated each project across a number of dimensions that are valued

00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:37.799
in my practice. You can pick aspects that suit your work, but the dimensions I picked

00:00:37.799 --> 00:00:44.799
cover if an analysis were replicable, modular, auditable, automated, and collaborative. So

00:00:44.799 --> 00:00:51.799
what were the results? Out of 55 projects, I scored an average of 3.8 out of 5. This

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:58.000
is good, but not great. So if I care so much about this, why wasn't my work rated higher?

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.880
Here are the lessons I took from my ReproRetro.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:06.760
Controversial opinion number one, not everything needs to be reproducible. While all projects

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:12.599
benefited from some aspect of reproducibility, the most important consideration for me was,

00:01:12.599 --> 00:01:17.480
how do you tell what needs to be reproducible?

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:22.320
Enter my Fiji test. So if you have a task that's sufficiently important, you may want

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:28.480
to consider the Fiji test. Aussies like Fiji because it's only a few hours away, but if

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:32.720
you're lying on a beach in holidays in Fiji, just spare a thought for your colleagues back

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:37.320
in the office. If they need to rerun some of your analysis, will they be able to find

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:43.400
it, understand your work, run it without too much fuss, and make reasonable enhancements

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:47.599
or small changes? The last thing you want while you're sipping your pina colada is to

00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:52.760
be disturbed by a weird phone call about some model that you trained.

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:56.639
When I looked at the type of analytics task I completed, not everything needed to pass

00:01:56.639 --> 00:02:03.080
the Fiji test. A lot of work in industry is ad hoc and quite simple. Commercial or a high

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:07.320
pressure environment, I think it's perfectly reasonable to have different standards on

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:11.600
workflow choices depending on the type of work and the return on investment that you

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:18.080
need. So long as a reasonable standard is maintained and as long as your team is consistent

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:23.399
with these choices. However, this may mean getting better at anticipating the full scope

00:02:23.399 --> 00:02:29.199
of the project before rushing into solving a problem, which can be a challenge. In addition,

00:02:29.199 --> 00:02:34.779
it gives you the freedom to pick a more lightweight and flexible workflow choice if desired.

00:02:34.779 --> 00:02:38.520
My next lesson was picking the right tools for the job. You know, I've been searching

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:43.720
for the biggest and best workflow choice, but I found it paid to have options. When

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:49.119
I examined my tooling and workflow options, the results of my repro retro varied. Using

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:54.279
a basic directory structure template to organize my projects was okay all round, but quickly

00:02:54.279 --> 00:03:00.000
got cumbersome. Notebooks like R Markdown were nicely replicable, but tended to be a

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.639
bit of a dumping ground for code. Drake, a more formal workflow system, carried a bit

00:03:05.639 --> 00:03:11.160
more overhead and more admin to get used to, but overall it enforced much better standards,

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:16.039
particularly around writing functional and modular code. While any system can be made

00:03:16.039 --> 00:03:20.960
arbitrarily sophisticated and do a good job, I found it more effective to have a few different

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:26.179
workflow choices available rather than try a one size fits all approach. All workflow

00:03:26.179 --> 00:03:30.800
choices are naturally optimized for certain applications, and I found it better to only

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:34.559
take on additional complexity when the job really needed it.

00:03:34.559 --> 00:03:40.720
Next, I found in my work I had a tendency to mistake replication for reproduction, and

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:46.160
the same goes for automation. Getting your code to rerun is only part of the solution,

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:50.199
so consider the factors that matter in your practice and be deliberate about what you

00:03:50.199 --> 00:03:56.960
optimize for, and use that to guide your workflow choice. And how do you do that? Well, do a

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:03.320
repro-retro. The process wasn't and isn't intended to be scientific or unbiased. The

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:09.080
true value of a repro-retro is in the self-reflection and improvement. So go and dig through your

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:14.000
old code and think about how you might do things better. If you want to learn more,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.320
you can reach out to me or visit my AnalysisFlow GitHub repo. I'd also like to acknowledge

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:24.480
and thank my collaborator Myles McBain for many interesting discussions in this space.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:25.320
Thank you and good luck.

00:04:26.959 --> 00:04:29.320
♪AT&T jingle♪

